******
[2] Chile (Los Lagos)
Date: Tue 24 Jan 2012
Source: Bio Bio Chile [in Spanish, trans. Mod.TY, edited]
http://www.biobiochile.cl/2012/01/24/hombre-es-ingresado-a-urgencia-tras-resultar-positivo-para-virus-hanta-en-puerto-montt.shtml

A 44-year-old man was taken from the Hornopiren locality to Puerto Montt for admission to the main medical facility of that city. This occurred after he was taken from the CESFAM [Family Health Center] in Hornopiren, after 9 days with a clinical picture of coughing, malaise, diarrhea without vomiting and without abdominal pain: symptoms that correspond to by the presence of [a] hantavirus [infection].

The patient is a fisherman in the area and, according to information from health authority there are no antecedents that he had been traveling in forests or along unimproved trails where long-tailed [pygmy rice] rats are present, his house being located on a fishing creek called El Manzano, some 20 km [12 mi] from Hornopiren, a place where this past Wednesday [18 Jan 2012] medical teams from the area went to initiate epidemiological and environmental investigations.

Once in Puerto Montt, the hantavirus rapid test was done with positive results. However, the physicians are awaiting the confirmation from the Public Health Institute in Santiago.

Meanwhile, the patient remains in stable condition and isolated in the emergency room of the [Puerto Montt] Base Hospital. He is being evaluated for a move to the intensive care unit on those premises.

[Published by Carolina Mardones; Information from Mauricio Barrientos]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Neither of the above reports indicates which hantavirus is responsible for these cases, but most likely Andes virus is involved. The areas where the infection occurred is endemic for this virus, and sporadic cases occur.

An image of the long-tailed pygmy rice rat (_Oligoryzomys longicaudatus_), the sigmodontine rodent host of Andes hantavirus, can be seen at http://www.bios.niu.edu/frayjorge/rod6.jpg.

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map showing the location of Nuble in the Bio Bio region can be accessed at http://healthmap.org/r/1HAM. A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map showing the location of Hornopiren in the Los Lagos region can be accessed at
http://healthmap.org/r/1HAL. - Mod.TY]
